An Issuer Identification Number (IIN), commonly known as a Bank Identification Number (BIN), is the first 6 to 8 digits of a payment card number (credit, debit, or prepaid). It uniquely identifies the institution issuing the card and the card network, facilitating secure, accurate transaction routing and fraud detection. 
Key Details About IINs:
Purpose: Identifies the bank/issuer and ensures secure transaction processing.
Location: Found on the front of credit, debit, and prepaid cards.
Structure: Traditionally 6 digits, but transitioning to 8 digits to expand available numbers.
First Digit: Known as the Major Industry Identifier (MII), identifying the industry, such as banking or travel.
Usage: Used by merchants for fraud detection (matching country/bank) and transaction routing.
Commonality: Used interchangeably with the term BIN (Bank Identification Number)
A Magnetic Ink Character Recognition (MICR) code is a 9-digit numerical code printed on cheques using special magnetic ink, uniquely identifying the bank branch to speed up clearing. It consists of a city code (first 3 digits), bank code (middle 3), and branch code (last 3), aiding in secure, automated processing. 
Key Details About MICR Codes:
Purpose: Facilitates fast and secure cheque processing via automated machines.
Location: Found at the bottom of a cheque leaf, usually next to the cheque number.
Structure:
First 3 digits: City code (often aligns with PIN code).
Next 3 digits: Bank code.
Last 3 digits: Branch code.
Benefits: Reduces manual errors, prevents fraud, and enables faster clearance.
Difference from IFSC: While the 11-digit alphanumeric IFSC is used for electronic transfers (NEFT/RTGS), the 9-digit numeric MICR is strictly for cheque clearing.

